data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — no longer accepts expression trees

The setter parameter changed from `Expression<Func<...>>` to `Func<...>`. Your manual expression tree code won't compile. **Replace it with a simple lambda:**

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The whole point of this breaking change was to eliminate the need for hand-built expression trees.

---

### 2. Complex type columns — names are now uniquified & nested paths changed

Two related changes:
- **Shared names get a numeric suffix** — `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` no longer silently share one column; the second gets `Street1`.
- **Nested complex types use the full path** — `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of just `BillingAddress_City`.

**To preserve existing column names**, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

If you **don't** pin names, EF will generate a new migration that renames the columns — which is fine for greenfield but will break existing databases without a migration.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. **Add it:**

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (has sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** method signatures on the interface — `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc. all got the same new parameter.
